This is an attempt at a streamlined and yet complete, relatively a priori/non- snooped model analysis. Some parts of the analysis have been moved into separate .R files: the overall workflow is

Limit all observations with all predictor variables > 0 and no biome 98/99; set biome as factor. Log and scale center variables as appropriate. This leaves us with 23 variables and 620 observations.

Model fitting

This can now be done semi-automatically (i.e., fit all combinations of random effects) by using the function fit_all from the mmd_utils.R file (sourced above), e.g. fit_all(response="mbirds_log")

However, the mmd_fitbatch.R code has already run all random-effects model combinations for all four response variables, so we can extract just one set of models (and profiles) this way:

load("allfits.RData")
focal <- "mamph_log"
results <- allfits[[focal]]
## profiles (from best model for each response variable/set of fits only)
load("allprofs.RData")
pp <- profList[[focal]] 
subset(aa2 <- AICtabx(results),dAIC<10)
##                                           dAIC df singular
## biome=int/flor_realms=int/biome_FR=diag    0.0 19     TRUE
## biome=diag/flor_realms=int/biome_FR=diag   3.8 23     TRUE
## biome=diag/flor_realms=int/biome_FR=int    3.9 19    FALSE
## biome=int/flor_realms=diag/biome_FR=diag   5.2 23     TRUE
## biome=diag/flor_realms=diag/biome_FR=int   6.5 23     TRUE
## biome=diag/flor_realms=diag/biome_FR=diag  8.6 27     TRUE
## get the name of the best model from the 27 fits
best_name <- get_best_name(results)
best_model <- results[[best_name]]
best_df <- attr(logLik(best_model),"df")

To get residuals use residuals(best_model,re.form=NULL); this uses all of the random effects.

Best non-singular model (by AIC) is biome=diag/flor_realms=int/biome_FR=int (19 parameters).

Pick CI type:

ci_method <- "Wald" ## or 'profile' or 'boot'
cc <- confint(best_model,method=ci_method)
best_coef <- tidy(best_model) %>% filter(term !="(Intercept)")
## drop spurious numeric values
tt <- gsub("\\.[0-9]","",best_coef$term)
## group separator -> bar
tt <- gsub("\\.(flor_realms$|biome$|biome_FR$)","|\\1",tt)
best_coef$term <- tt
nppcv_var <- best_coef$nppcv_var <- grepl("NPP_cv",tt)
re_var <- grepl("^(sd|cor)",tt) & !nppcv_var
otherfix_var <- !re_var & !nppcv_var
ee <- best_coef$estimate
## order by magnitude within
## (1) random effects (non-NPPcv)
## (2) non-NPPcv, non-RE
## (3) NPPcv
best_coef$term <- factor(tt,
      levels=c((tt[re_var])[order(ee[re_var])],
               (tt[otherfix_var])[order(ee[otherfix_var])],
               (tt[nppcv_var])[order(ee[nppcv_var])]))
mm <- match(tt,rownames(cc))
mm[is.na(mm)] <- match("sigma",rownames(cc))
best_coef$lwr <- cc[mm,"2.5 %"]
best_coef$upr <- cc[mm,"97.5 %"]
best_coef$sd_var <- grepl("^sd",best_coef$term)
best_coef$nppcv_fac <- factor(best_coef$nppcv_var,
                              labels=c("non-NPPcv terms",
                                       "NPPcv terms"))
ggplot(best_coef,aes(estimate,term,
                     colour=sd_var))+
    scale_colour_manual(values=c("black","red"),guide=FALSE)+
    geom_point()+
    geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin=lwr, # estimate-1.96*std.error,
                       xmax=upr, # estimate+1.96*std.error
                       ),height=0)+
    geom_vline(xintercept=0,lty=2)+
    facet_wrap(~nppcv_fac,scale="free")+
    labs(x="",y="")

Interpreting scales: In principle the (centered) coefficient of variation and the log-scaled effects should be directly comparable, since both are on a proportional scale. That is, a change of 0.1 in CV of NPP corresponds to an increase in standard deviation of 10% of the mean NPP; a change of 0.1 in log NPP corresponds approximately to a 10% increase in the NPP (actually $(0.1)=round(exp(0.1),2)). None of this explains particularly well why the NPP_cv effects are so large (and uncertain).

fix_NAs <- function(rem,model) {
    if (!is.null(nastuff <- attr(model.frame(model),"na.action"))) {
        return(napredict(nastuff,rem))
    } else return(rem)
}
rem1 <- fix_NAs(remef(best_model,ran="all"),best_model)
if (length(rem1)==nrow(ecoreg)) {
    ## if it worked ...
    ecoreg$rem1 <- rem1
    ## update previous plot: 
    print(gg0 %+% ecoreg +  ## incorporate new column 
          geom_point(aes(y=rem1,colour=biome,shape=flor_realms)))  ## change response var
}

ecoreg$rem2 <- fix_NAs(remef(best_model,ran="all",
                             fix=c("NPP_log","NPP_cv_ctr","Feat_cv_ctr"),grouping=TRUE),
                       best_model)
ecoreg$rem3 <- fix_NAs(remef(best_model,ran="all",
                             fix=c("NPP_log","NPP_cv_ctr","Feat_log"),grouping=TRUE),
                       best_model)
## FIXME: drop dimensions on Feat_cv_ctr upstream
gg1 <- ggplot(ecoreg,aes(c(Feat_cv_ctr),rem3))+
    geom_point(aes(colour=biome,shape=flor_realms))+
